+### RSS and Atom
+
+Add each feed separately during onboarding. OpenWiki preserves each subscription
+as a stable source instance (`rss-1`, `rss-2`, and so on), so one feed's HTTP
+validators and entry cursor cannot affect another. Run every subscription with
+`openwiki ingest rss --print`, one subscription with
+`openwiki ingest rss-2 --print`, or all configured sources with
+`openwiki ingest all --print`. The shared scheduled ingestion runs all enabled
+source instances; `openwiki cron pause rss`, `resume`, and `delete` use the
+normal connector schedule controls.
+
+Advanced manual configuration uses the source instance's `connectorConfig` in
+`~/.openwiki/onboarding.json`:
+
+```json
+{
+  "enabled": true,
+  "feedUrl": "https://example.com/feed.xml",
+  "maxBytes": 2097152,
+  "maxItems": 100,
+  "timeoutMs": 15000
+}
+```
+
+Feed URLs must use HTTP or HTTPS and cannot contain userinfo or secret-like
+query parameters. Put no credentials in feed URLs or connector files. Request
+time is bounded to 100–30000 ms, response size to 128 bytes–10 MiB, and emitted
+items to 1–500; defaults are 15 seconds, 2 MiB, and 100 items.
+
+The connector sends saved `ETag` and `Last-Modified` validators and keeps a
+bounded identity/content-hash cursor per source instance. A rerun emits only new
+entries or entries whose normalized content changed. Normalized entry files and
+manifests preserve feed URL, source instance, entry URL and GUID/Atom ID, title,
+author, publication time, capture time, and provenance under
+`~/.openwiki/connectors/rss/raw/<runId>/`. Conditional and cursor state stays in
+`~/.openwiki/connectors/rss/state.json`. Connector directories and files retain
+OpenWiki's private `0700`/`0600` permissions and Git exclusion.
+
